    body: `
      <p>Inside every medication package you purchase in Italy, you'll find a detailed information sheet called the foglio illustrativo (package insert). This document contains comprehensive information about your medication, including how to use it, potential side effects, and important safety warnings. Understanding how to read this document is essential for safe medication use.</p>

      <h3>What is the Foglio Illustrativo?</h3>
      <p>The foglio illustrativo is a legally required document that accompanies all medications sold in Italy and throughout the European Union. It's typically a printed sheet folded inside the medication package, and it contains detailed information about the medication in Italian. This document is your primary resource for understanding your medication once you've taken it home from the pharmacy.</p>

      <h3>Standard Sections of the Foglio Illustrativo</h3>
      <p>The Italian foglio illustrativo follows a standardized format established by European regulations. Understanding this structure helps you find the information you need quickly.</p>

      <h3>1. Nome Commerciale e Composizione (Brand Name and Composition)</h3>
      <p>The document begins with the brand name of the medication. Below this, you'll find the composition section, which lists the active ingredient(s) and their quantities. You'll also see the inactive ingredients (eccipiente), which are the substances that help deliver the active ingredient but don't have a therapeutic effect themselves.</p>

      <p>For example: "Paracetamolo 500 mg per compressa" means each tablet contains 500 milligrams of paracetamol.</p>

      <h3>2. Forma Farmaceutica (Pharmaceutical Form)</h3>
      <p>This section indicates the physical form of the medication: tablet (compresse), capsule (capsule), liquid (soluzione), drops (gocce), powder (polvere), suppository (supposta), cream (crema), or ointment (unguento). This information is important because it affects how you'll use the medication.</p>

      <h3>3. Indicazioni Terapeutiche (Therapeutic Indications)</h3>
      <p>This section explains what the medication is used for—essentially, which conditions or symptoms it treats. It's important to verify that your condition matches one of the listed indications. If you have questions about whether this medication is right for you, this is the section to review.</p>

      <p>For example, a package insert might state that the medication is used for "temporary relief of minor aches and pains due to headache, muscular aches, backache, minor arthritis pain, the common cold, toothache, menstrual cramps, and fever."</p>

      <h3>4. Controindicazioni (Contraindications)</h3>
      <p>Contraindications are situations in which you should absolutely not take the medication because it could be dangerous. These might include specific health conditions, allergies, or other circumstances. This is a critical section to read carefully.</p>

      <p>If you have any of the listed contraindications, do not take this medication. Instead, contact your doctor or pharmacist for an alternative.</p>

      <h3>5. Precautions (Precauzioni e Avvertenze Speciali)</h3>
      <p>Unlike contraindications, precautions are warnings that don't necessarily mean you can't take the medication, but that you should be extra careful. This section might include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Special precautions about when to use the medication</li>
        <li>Groups that need to be especially careful (pregnant women, elderly, children)</li>
        <li>Situations that require medical supervision</li>
        <li>Information about driving or operating machinery</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>6. Effetti Indesiderati (Side Effects/Adverse Reactions)</h3>
      <p>This section lists possible side effects, organized by frequency. The frequency categories used in Italian package inserts are:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Molto comune (very common):</strong> Affects more than 1 in 10 people</li>
        <li><strong>Comune (common):</strong> Affects 1 in 10 to 1 in 100 people</li>
        <li><strong>Non comune (uncommon):</strong> Affects 1 in 100 to 1 in 1,000 people</li>
        <li><strong>Raro (rare):</strong> Affects 1 in 1,000 to 1 in 10,000 people</li>
        <li><strong>Molto raro (very rare):</strong> Affects fewer than 1 in 10,000 people</li>
      </ul>

      <p>This information helps you understand which side effects are relatively common and which are extremely rare. It's important to remember that listed side effects don't necessarily mean you'll experience them.</p>

      <h3>7. Posologia e Modo di Somministrazione (Dosage and How to Take It)</h3>
      <p>This is one of the most important sections. It tells you:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>How much of the medication to take</li>
        <li>How often to take it</li>
        <li>Whether it should be taken with food or water</li>
        <li>Special instructions for specific groups (children, elderly, patients with liver/kidney disease)</li>
        <li>How long to continue taking the medication</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Always follow these instructions carefully. If you're unsure about the dosage, ask your pharmacist or doctor.</p>

      <h3>8. Sovradosaggio (Overdose)</h3>
      <p>This section explains what to do if you accidentally take more medication than prescribed or recommended. It describes symptoms of overdose and what actions to take. If you suspect an overdose, this is the section to consult and then contact emergency services or poison control.</p>

      <h3>9. Conservazione (Storage Instructions)</h3>
      <p>This section provides detailed instructions on how to properly store your medication to maintain its effectiveness:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Temperatura ambiente:</strong> Room temperature</li>
        <li><strong>In frigorifero:</strong> In the refrigerator</li>
        <li><strong>Protetto da luce e umidità:</strong> Protected from light and moisture</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Always follow these instructions to ensure your medication remains safe and effective until its expiration date.</p>

      <h3>10. Scadenza e Numero di Lotto (Expiration Date and Lot Number)</h3>
      <p>This section includes the expiration date (scadenza) and lot/batch number (numero di lotto). Never use medication after the expiration date.</p>

      <h3>11. Titolare dell'Autorizzazione all'Immissione in Commercio (Manufacturer Information)</h3>
      <p>This section provides the name and address of the company that holds the marketing authorization for the medication. This information is useful if you need to contact the manufacturer with questions or to report side effects.</p>

      <h3>Tips for Reading the Foglio Illustrativo</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Read the entire document, not just the dosage section</li>
        <li>Pay special attention to contraindications and precautions</li>
        <li>Keep the package insert for reference even after you finish the medication</li>
        <li>If you don't understand something, ask your pharmacist</li>
        <li>If you experience side effects not listed, contact your doctor</li>
        <li>Check the expiration date before taking any medication</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Using Online Resources</h3>
      <p>If you need help understanding the Italian, many online tools can assist. You can use translation apps, but always verify critical information with your pharmacist or doctor rather than relying solely on automated translation, which can sometimes make mistakes with medical terminology.</p>

      <h3>Conclusion</h3>
      <p>The foglio illustrativo is your gateway to safe and informed medication use. By taking the time to read and understand this document, you ensure that you're using your medication correctly and safely. Your pharmacist is always available to help explain anything you don't understand, so don't hesitate to ask questions.</p>
    `
